         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">10/10/79. ¶  ¶ It was with much gratification, dear Sir Joseph, that I received this day through the Governor your two very kind letters. ¶  ¶ The views, taken by our venerable Bentham, on honors from...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">79.10.10</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 246-7.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">10/10/79.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It was with much gratification, dear Sir Joseph, that I received this day through the Governor your two very kind letters.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letters not found.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The views, taken by our venerable Bentham, on honors from the throne are extreme; — and as he has <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">rendered</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">important services</hi>
               </seg> to <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">the Australian</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Colonies</hi>
               </seg>, through his elucidation of their Floras, he comes quite within the reach of an order, confined to the mediterranean &amp; colonial possessions of Britain.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">At that period, the Order of St Michael and St George was so confined.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In many instances men of science must make some sacrifices of their own feelings for the sake of their social status, family connections, official position, &amp; where a distinction has a value even for a Lady, she must also be considered.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When you see Sir Henry Barkly, pray remember me kindly to him, and thank him for his continued goodness towards me. I wished he was here again! Assuredly the British Government will still further utilize his great administrative abilities.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Barkly, who was retired on a pension in 1877, was nominated as one of the 'Commissioners on the defence of British possessions and commerce abroad' on 8 December 1879. He did not receive a further appointment as a colonial Governor (DNB).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sir Michael Hicks-Beach must be a particularly kind and enlightened man. I hope that some day it will be in my power, to evince to the right Honorable Baronet actively my gratitude for the consideration, which he has shown me.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to M. Hicks Beach, 29 September 1879.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me thank you also for devoting again a plate to one of my plants. It almost brings <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">tears</hi>
               </seg> into my eyes! The foliage of this 6445 will bring <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Guichenotia</hi>
               </seg> to mind, G. ledifolia in its small state being not dissimilar to Lasiopet. Baueri I gathered seeds of it in 1867 in W.A. My "native plants"<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B79.06.04.</p>
               </note> will not be free from short-comings, but a foundation for a more perfect work will thereby be gained. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Perhaps you will remember, dear Sir Joseph, that I strongly urged to you &amp; Mr Bentham, when you commenced the genera,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> to include the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> among the higher developed plants,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See for example M to G. Bentham, 24 January 1862, and M to W. Hooker, 29 January 1862 (in this edition as <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>62-01-29a).</p>
               </note> to which you mainly objected, because it would be better to keep to D.C., as the prodromus<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A. P. de Candolle (1823-73).</p>
               </note> was everywhere in use. Still, I foresee, that in a new edition you will in due time amalgamate the <name key="Apetalae">Apetalae</name> with Calyci- &amp; <name key="Thalamiflorae">Thalamiflorae</name>. But a few instances of difficulty occur, e.g. with <name key="Casuarina">Casuarina</name>e.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is kind of you to support Profess. M’Coy at the Council of the R.S.,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Royal Society. See M to T. Huxley, 8 June 1879, and M to J. Hooker, 8 June 1879 (in this edition as <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>79-06-08b).</p>
               </note> and I will act on your advice concerning the certificate.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See Royal Society nomination certificate for Frederick McCoy (in this edition as 80-03-04a). </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>remembrance</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
